# Main Results

## Primary Finding

**The historical average equity premium consistently outperforms predictive regression forecasts.**

| Predictor | In-sample R² | Out-of-sample R² (1965-2005) |
|-----------|--------------|------------------------------|
| D/P | 1.96% | **-1.42%** |
| D/Y | 1.89% | **-1.28%** |
| E/P | 1.12% | **-1.95%** |
| B/M | 0.52% | **-0.55%** |
| TBL | 0.36% | **-0.17%** |
| TMS | 0.21% | **-0.16%** |
| DFY | 0.28% | **-0.10%** |

*Note: Negative out-of-sample R² means historical average outperforms.*

## Key Patterns

1. **In-sample vs Out-of-sample disconnect**: Variables with positive in-sample R² often have negative out-of-sample R²

2. **Instability**: Coefficient estimates are unstable over time—signs and magnitudes fluctuate

3. **No single winner**: No predictor consistently beats the benchmark across all subperiods

4. **Forecast combination fails**: Equal-weighted combination of all predictors also underperforms

## Subsample Analysis

- **Pre-1970**: Some predictors show modest out-of-sample success
- **Post-1970**: Nearly all predictors fail
- **1990s bull market**: Valuation ratios particularly fail (markets kept rising despite "overvaluation" signals)

